We need to give the option where we allow the developer to make review the components that would be added and later on edit/add/change them. issue.title: Reopen email submission ports

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
A while ago, we blocked outbound traffic from Zos VMs to certain ports used for email (see https://github.com/threefoldtech/zos/issues/1987).

That was implemented as this firewall rule:

https://github.com/threefoldtech/zos/blob/0199ee83ff9918918f18fd25fd7ba1cdc1c7abce/cmds/modules/networkd/nft.go#L53

This was a success, in the sense that we don't have anymore complaints about Zos nodes sending spam email. On the other hand, we are getting some questions about why VMs aren't able to communicate on ports 465 and 587.

The summary of what the common email ports are used for is as follows:

* 25 - used for sending mail between mail servers (this is the main concern for spam)
* 465 & 587 - used for submitting mail to a mail providers server, with authentication (not really a concern for spam)

Given that, I'd like to propose that we reopen ports 465 and 587. Have also discussed with @delandtj who is in agreement that this should be safe.

comment.body: I'd open the ports, but we should be able to KYC the opening of the ports in the near future. Spammers need to die a gruesome death, or at least have their family jewels removed and/or crushed, so we need to know them to be able to find them.

issue.title: Refactor: Split large CLI command files into logical modules
issue.body:
## Summary

This PR refactors the large CLI command files into focused, maintainable modules. The refactoring improves code organization while maintaining 100% backward compatibility.

## Files Refactored

###  **`email.rs`** (867 lines  6 modules)
- **`analytics.rs`** - Email tracking and analytics functionality
- **`core.rs`** - Core email operations (send, setup)
- **`providers.rs`** - Provider operations (test, configure, switch)
- **`queue.rs`** - Queue operations (status, process, clear)
- **`templates.rs`** - Template management (list, validate, render)
- **`testing.rs`** - Testing/capture functionality (capture, list, show, clear, export)

###  **`queue.rs`** (795 lines  3 modules)
- **`queue_work.rs`** - Work processing functionality for background job execution
- **`queue_status.rs`** - Status monitoring functionality for queue inspection
- **`queue_scheduler.rs`** - Scheduled commands and daemon functionality for cron-like jobs

###  **`auth.rs`** (761 lines  3 modules)
- **`auth_setup.rs`** - Auth system setup and configuration
- **`auth_scaffold.rs`** - Scaffolding (user models, controllers, migrations)
- **`auth_generators.rs`** - Key generation functionality

###  **`new.rs`** (492 lines  2 modules)
- **`new_app.rs`** - Main application creation functionality
- **`new_templates.rs`** - Template generation and file creation

###  **`interactive_setup.rs`** (410 lines  2 modules)
- **`interactive_wizard.rs`** - Interactive project setup wizard functionality
- **`interactive_config.rs`** - Configuration collection and generation

## Key Benefits

-  **Improved maintainability**: Each module has a single, focused responsibility
-  **Better code organization**: Related functionality is grouped together logically
-  **Enhanced readability**: Smaller, more manageable files are easier to navigate
-  **Zero breaking changes**: All existing functionality preserved with the same public API
-  **Consistent patterns**: Modular structure follows the same pattern across all commands
-  **Future development**: New features can be added to the appropriate module

## Testing

All functionality has been thoroughly tested:

-  **Build verification**: `cargo build` completes successfully with no errors
-  **CLI functionality**: All commands work exactly as before
-  **Help system**: All help commands display correctly
-  **Module integration**: Proper re-export structure maintains original public interface

### Command Testing Results
```bash
$ elifrs --help        #  Main help works
$ elifrs email --help  #  Email commands work  
$ elifrs queue --help  #  Queue commands work
$ elifrs auth --help   #  Auth commands work
```

## Technical Details

### Module Structure
Each refactored command follows this pattern:
```
crates/cli/src/commands/[command]/
 mod.rs              # Module declarations and re-exports
 [command]_[area].rs # Focused functionality modules
 [command]_[area].rs # Additional modules as needed
```

### Backward Compatibility
- All original imports continue to work without modification
- External code using these modules requires no changes
- All CLI commands maintain their exact same behavior and help text

## Code Quality

- **Focused modules**: Each module has a clear, single responsibility
- **Clean separation**: Related functionality is properly grouped
- **Consistent imports**: All dependencies correctly maintained across modules
- **Documentation**: Each module includes appropriate documentation
- **Error handling**: All original error handling logic preserved

 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.ai/code)

ci: Use a mirror for musl

We pretty often get at least one job failed because of failure to pull
the musl git repo. Switch this to the unofficial mirror [1] which should
be more reliable.

Link: https://github.com/kraj/musl [1]

ci: Upgrade ubuntu:25.04 for the PowerPC64LE test

Update the last remaining image.

For this to work, the `QEMU_CPU=POWER8` configuration needed to be
dropped to avoid a new SIGILL. Doing some debugging locally, the crash
comes from an `extswsli` (per `powerpc:common64` in gdb-multiarch) in
the `ld64.so` available with PowerPC, which qemu rejects when set to
power8. Testing a build with `+crt-static` hits the same issue at a
`maddld` in `__libc_start_main_impl`.

Rust isn't needed to reproduce this:

    $ cat a.c
    #include <stdio.h>

    int main() {
            printf("Hello, world!\n");
    }
    $ powerpc64le-linux-gnu-gcc a.c
    $ QEMU_CPU=power8 QEMU_LD_PREFIX=/usr/powerpc64le-linux-gnu/ ./a.out
    qemu: uncaught target signal 4 (Illegal instruction) - core dumped
    Illegal instruction

So the cross toolchain provided by Debian must have a power9 baseline
rather than rustc's power8. Alternatively, qemu may be incorrectly
rejecting these instructions (I can't find a source on whether or not
they should be available for power8). Testing instead with the `-musl`
toolchain and ppc linker from musl.cc works correctly.

In any case, things work with the default qemu config so it seems fine
to drop. The env was originally added in 5d164a4edafb ("fix the
powerpc64le target") but whatever the problem was there appears to no
longer be relevant.

Enable tests that were skipped on PowerPC

Most of these were skipped because of a bug with the platform
implementation, or some kind of crash unwinding. Since the upgrade to
Ubuntu 25.04, these all seem to be resolved with the exception of a bug
in the host `__floatundisf` [1].

[1] https://github.com/rust-lang/compiler-builtins/pull/384#issuecomment-740413334

Add non-temporal note for maskmoveu_si128

Like any other non-temporal instructions this has additional safety requirements
due to the mismatch with the Rust memory model. It is vital to know when using
this instruction.

Merge pull request #1885 from 197g/maskmove-is-non-temporal

Add non-temporal note for maskmoveu_si128

expand the issue template for new lints

When I first tried contributing to clippy,
I encountered the problem that a lot of lint suggestions overlapped
with existing lints, so I would spend a bunch of time implementing
something only to figure out it wasn't actually needed.

The "comparison with existing lints" field should hopefully reduce
this somewhat, while not incresing the burden of
requesting a new lint too much due to not being mandatory.

Enable tests that were skipped on aarch64

The LLVM issue was resolved a while ago, these should no longer be a
problem.

Enable skipped `f32` and `f64` multiplication tests

The fix has since made it to nightly, so the skips here can be removed.

Use `x86_no_sse` configuration in more places

Emit `x86_no_sse` in the compiler-builtins (and builtins-test) build
script, and use it to simplify `all(target_arch = "x86",
not(target_fefature = "sse))` configuration.

# Phase 2: Brownfield Modernization - Spring Boot 3.5.4 + Gradle 8.14.3 + Complete Swagger Integration ## Summary This PR completes the brownfield modernization of SmartClaims360 by upgrading to the latest stable versions and adding comprehensive Swagger/OpenAPI documentation for all 8 REST endpoints. The application has been modernized from Spring Boot 3.1.2 to 3.5.4 and Gradle 8.2.1 to 8.14.3, while maintaining full backward compatibility and adding extensive API documentation. **Key Changes:** - **Version Upgrades**: Spring Boot 3.1.2 3.5.4, Gradle 8.2.1 8.14.3 - **Swagger Integration**: Added springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui:2.7.0 with comprehensive annotations - **Complete API Documentation**: All 8 endpoints now have detailed @Operation annotations with realistic examples - **Schema Documentation**: All DTOs and entities have @Schema annotations with field descriptions - **Governance**: Added CODEOWNERS and Dependabot configuration for automated maintenance - **Enhanced Testing**: Added Swagger integration tests and updated README with detailed examples ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human ** CRITICAL - Must Verify (High Risk Items):** - [ ] **Application Startup**: Verify the application starts successfully with Spring Boot 3.5.4 and Gradle 8.14.3 (`./gradlew bootRun`) - [ ] **Swagger UI Accessibility**: Navigate to `http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html` and confirm all 8 endpoints are properly documented - [ ] **Example Payload Testing**: Test at least 2-3 example requests through Swagger UI to ensure they work correctly (especially AI endpoints) - [ ] **Full Test Suite**: Run `./gradlew clean build test` to ensure no regressions from version upgrades (should still pass 41+ tests) ** IMPORTANT - Should Verify:** - [ ] **API Documentation Accuracy**: Compare Swagger examples with actual API responses to ensure consistency - [ ] **Schema Validation**: Verify @Schema annotations display correctly in Swagger UI for all DTOs (ClaimRequest, FraudScoreResponse, ValidationResponse, RoutingSuggestion, Claim) **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Start application and access Swagger UI 2. Test claim creation through Swagger UI using provided examples 3. Test AI validation and fraud scoring endpoints with different risk levels 4. issue.title: Feature Request: Add Sidecar Mode for mTLS Using Envoy
issue.body:
**Problem Statement:**
Currently, mTLS is enabled by directly mounting certificates into the main container. This requires changes or dependencies in the main application for certificate handling and TLS termination. Many legacy or third-party applications cannot be modified easily, which makes adoption harder.

**Solution:**
Introduce a sidecar mode where mTLS is handled by injecting an Envoy sidecar container.

- The sidecar will manage certificate lifecycle, TLS termination, and secure communication.
- The main container will communicate with Envoy over plain HTTP (localhost).
- Envoy will transparently handle inbound and outbound TLS with mTLS enforcement.

Benefits:

- No changes needed in the main container/application code.
- Works seamlessly with legacy or black-box workloads.
- Aligns with common service mesh practices (e.g., Istio, Linkerd).

**Additional context**

- The operator can expose a toggle in the CRD or annotation (e.g., auto-mtls.kupher.io/mode=sidecar) to enable Envoy injection.
- Certificates can still be provisioned via cert-manager and mounted into the Envoy container.
- This feature will make the solution more flexible and usable for a wider range of workloads.

rclcpp::WallRate is preferable to rclcpp::Rate, because with rclcpp::WallRate `rate.sleep()` wont stall due to backward system clock adjustments (e.g., a one-day rollback).

pull_request.title: Feature/frontend streamlit
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces improvements to frontend deep-linking compatibility and adds structured logging to the backend. The most significant changes are the addition of compatibility helpers for handling URL query parameters in Streamlit across different versions, and the setup of JSON logging for better observability.

**Frontend deep-linking compatibility:**

* Added `_get_query_param` and `_set_query_param` helper functions in `src/frontend/app.py` to handle reading and setting query parameters across different Streamlit versions, improving robustness for deep-linking to game details.
* Updated the logic for setting the selected game ID and updating the URL to use the new compatibility helpers, replacing direct calls to `st.get_query_params()` and `st.experimental_set_query_params`.
* Updated documentation in `README.md` to clarify that the app now reads URL query params for deep-linking, reflecting the new compatibility logic.

**Backend logging improvements:**

* Added a new `src/backend/logger_config.py` module to configure structured JSON logging using `pythonjsonlogger`, improving log format and maintainability.

# Phase 2: Brownfield Modernization - Spring Boot 3.5.4 + Gradle 8.14.3 + Complete Swagger Integration ## Summary This PR completes the brownfield modernization of SmartClaims360 by upgrading to the latest stable versions and adding comprehensive Swagger/OpenAPI documentation for all 8 REST endpoints. The application has been modernized from Spring Boot 3.1.2 to 3.5.4 and Gradle 8.2.1 to 8.14.3, while maintaining full backward compatibility and adding extensive API documentation. **Key Changes:** - **Version Upgrades**: Spring Boot 3.1.2 3.5.4, Gradle 8.2.1 8.14.3 - **Swagger Integration**: Added springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui:2.7.0 with comprehensive annotations - **Complete API Documentation**: All 8 endpoints now have detailed @Operation annotations with realistic examples - **Schema Documentation**: All DTOs and entities have @Schema annotations with field descriptions - **Governance**: Added CODEOWNERS and Dependabot configuration for automated maintenance - **Enhanced Testing**: Added Swagger integration tests and updated README with detailed examples ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human ** CRITICAL - Must Verify (High Risk Items):** - [ ] **Application Startup**: Verify the application starts successfully with Spring Boot 3.5.4 and Gradle 8.14.3 (`./gradlew bootRun`) - [ ] **Swagger UI Accessibility**: Navigate to `http://localhost:8080/swagger-ui.html` and confirm all 8 endpoints are properly documented - [ ] **Example Payload Testing**: Test at least 2-3 example requests through Swagger UI to ensure they work correctly (especially AI endpoints) - [ ] **Full Test Suite**: Run `./gradlew clean build test` to ensure no regressions from version upgrades (should still pass 41+ tests) ** IMPORTANT - Should Verify:** - [ ] **API Documentation Accuracy**: Compare Swagger examples with actual API responses to ensure consistency - [ ] **Schema Validation**: Verify @Schema annotations display correctly in Swagger UI for all DTOs (ClaimRequest, FraudScoreResponse, ValidationResponse, RoutingSuggestion, Claim) **Recommended Test Plan:** 1. Start application and access Swagger UI 2. Test claim creation through Swagger UI using provided examples 3. Test AI validation and fraud scoring endpoints with different risk levels 4. Verify error responses (404, 400) match documented examples 5. Confirm all endpoint examples in README still work via curl --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% flowchart TD BuildGradle["build.gradle

repo.name: smartclaims360
repo.description: SmartClaims360** is an AI-assisted, full-stack claims processing platform that automates and optimizes the claims lifecycle from intake to settlement. It integrates AI-driven validation, fraud detection, intelligent routing, and real-time dashboards to deliver faster, more accurate, and more transparent claim handling.
